@node intro "Let's start a new age in the GUIs for Visage!!!"

@{b}Introduction@{ub}

Visage is one of the best picture viewer for the Amiga, but is CLI only: I love
command line programs because I use the shell for everything, but I know that
many people prefer a graphical interface: so I have written this GUI for Visage,
using the excellent Gui4Cli language: so to use the GUI you must have Gui4Cli
installed, and of course Visage!!!

So let's see @{"how to use" link uso} this powerful & wonderful GUI!!! :-)

@endnode

@node requi "System requirements?!? PII,64M Ram,3Dfx Card,150M HD space,Win '98...NO!!!"

@{b}System Requirements@{ub}

- An Amiga
- At least WB 2.0 (I think...)
- Visage (version 39.15 or above) and Gui4Cli (with their own requirements :-)

You can find the two needed programs on Aminet:

Visage:  gfx/show/Visage.lha
Gui4Cli: dev/gui/Gui4Cli.lha

@{b}WARNING:@{ub} the "random" and "gray" options properly works only with Visage 39.15
or above, because the parameters are changed from older versions: if you use an
older version you can not use these options.

@endnode

@node uso "How to use it..."

@{b}Usage@{ub}

If you are an regular user of Visage you can almost use the GUI without reading
this guide: for a deep description of the various options please read the Visage
documentation, but here I'll give a quick overview.

@{b}First of all@{ub}: place a copy of the Visage executable anywhere in your command
path (i.e. in the C: assign), or the GUI won't find it!

Then, if you have Gui4Cli properly installed, you may have a little program
called 'gui' in C: this is used to launch the Gui4Cli scripts: so launch Visgui
by clicking on his icon or by shell typing: 'gui Visgui.gc'.

The Visgui window has the following items:

@{b}The listview@{ub}: this is used to select the files and dirs to act on: select the
items with the mouse: multi-selections can be made by simply holding down the
left mouse button and moving the mouse: you can even use the arrow keys to
scroll the contents of the listview.

@{b}The control buttons@{ub}: how can you find less intuitive buttons?

@{b} Parent@{ub}: move to the parent directory.
@{b} Root@{ub}: move to the root directory.
@{b} Disks@{ub}: show the disks and the assigns.
@{b} All@{ub}: select all the files and dirs in the current dir.
@{b} None@{ub}: de-select all the files and dirs in the current dir.

@{b}The options control checkboxes@{ub}:

(@{b}NOTE:@{ub} Visgui only covers some of the many Visage's options)

@{b} Random@{ub}: show the pics in random order.
@{b} Datatypes@{ub}: use datatypes.
@{b} Forever@{ub}: show the pics until aborted (with RMB or ESC key).
@{b} Gray@{ub}: show the pics in greyscale.
@{b} Scale@{ub}: scale the pics to fit screen.
@{b} NoIFF@{ub}: use datatypes for IFF pics.
@{b} NoGIF@{ub}: use datatypes for GIF pics.
@{b} NoJPEG@{ub}: use datatypes for JPEG pics.
@{b} Lowmem@{ub}: disable background loading.
@{b} CLI Output@{ub}: usually you won't see any text output: with this options you can
             open a window showing the Visage's output.
@{b} Screenmode Requester@{ub}: you can select a screenmode before displaying the pics
@{b} Delay@{ub}: a delay (in seconds) between the pics.
@{b} Fade@{ub}: different levels of fade (only works with some image formats)
@{b} Times@{ub}: number of times to display the pics.

@{b}Command@{ub}: here you can type a command to execute to the currently displayed file,
         pressing the 'E' key: i.e. if you type: 'delete []' (without the ''),
         pressing the 'E' key will cause the current file to be deleted, or if
         you type 'copy [] ram:', pressing the 'E' key you can copy the current
         file to ram:. There's no need to enclose the command in quotes!!!
         (That's great!!! :^)

@{b}File handling buttons@{ub}:

@{b}Dest. Dir@{ub}: show the dir where the files/dirs will be copied or moved using the
            respective buttons: type in the dir or select it pressing the @{b}'Sel'@{ub}
            button.
@{b} Copy@{ub}: copy the selected files/dirs to the Dest. Dir.
@{b} Move@{ub}: move the selected files/dirs to the Dest. Dir.
@{b} Rename@{ub}: rename the selected files/dirs: pressing the @{b}'Abort'@{ub} button will abort
         the operation: after renaming the current dir is refreshed.
@{b} Delete@{ub}: delete the selected files/dirs: @{b}BE CAREFUL@{ub}: if the checkbox at the
         right of the 'Delete' button is active, an 'Are you sure?' type
         requester will appear for each entry, otherwise the files/dirs will be
         deleted without asking.

@{b}View@{ub}: view the selected files: if a dir is selected, then all the files in that
      dir will be displayed. Pressing the @{b}right mouse button@{ub} is equivalent of
      pressing the View button.

@{b}HOW TO EXIT:@{ub}

To exit from Visgui, press @{b}Ctrl-S@{ub} to show the @{b}Gui4Cli status requester@{ub} and then:

-if you wish to close Visgui but keep Gui4Cli running, click on @{b}Unload@{ub}, select
VISGUI.GC and RENAME.GC from the file requester and click on @{b}Unload@{ub} (still in the
file requester! :-)

-if you wish to quit completely from Gui4Cli (and of course from Visgui too!),
click on @{b}QUIT@{ub}.

In fact closing the Visgui's window seems to close the program, but Gui4Cli
makes a little mess in some cases, so is better to use the previous method!

@endnode

